Example R Markdown Document

This is an R Markdown document. An extremely powerful type of R file. This lets us combine prose and code. So that we can better document our analyses. R Markdown can be used for creating word or pdf documents, resumes, websites, books, and so much more!

What is Markdown?

Markdown is a syntax that lets us style our documents. Think of markdown as a simpler version of microsoft word with so many fewer clicks.

Heres an overview of Markdown syntax that you can use anywhere on GitHub.com or in your own text files.

Headers

# This is an h1 tag
## This is an h2 tag
###### This is an h6 tag

This is an h1 tag

This is an h2 tag

This is an h6 tag

Emphasis

*This text will be italic*
_This will also be italic_

**This text will be bold**
__This will also be bold__

_You **can** combine them_

This text will be italic This will also be italic

This text will be bold This will also be bold

You can combine them

Lists

Unordered

* Item 1
* Item 2
  * Item 2a
  * Item 2b
  • Item 1
  • Item 2
    • Item 2a
    • Item 2b

Ordered

1. Item 1
1. Item 2
1. Item 3
   1. Item 3a
   1. Item 3b
  1. Item 1
  2. Item 2
  3. Item 3
    1. Item 3a
    2. Item 3b

Images

R Markdown and code chunks

The powerhouse of R Markdown (Rmd) are code chunks. Code chunks start with ```{r} on its own line and end with ``` on its own line as well.

Create code chunks with the shortcut cntrl + opt + i.

Code chunks have lots of options. You can explore them with the little gear at the far right of the code chunk. We can choose to only show the output of the code and not the code itself by setting the chunk argument echo = FALSE.

## [1] "hello class!"

This is super helpful if you want to create a plot but not show anyone the code.

## Loading data for The Urban Informatics Toolkit.

To change the type of document that you will create press the drop down next to the blue ball of yarn which says Knit. This will change the output to something like pdf_document.

The top section delineated with --- is called the header. This is used to store metadata for the document such as the title, author (thats you!), and the output type.

With R Markdown we can use cool packages like kableExtra, reactable, and gt to create pretty tables to look at!

library(dplyr)

airbnb_hosts %>% 
  group_by(since_year) %>% 
  summarise(n_superhosts = sum(superhost, na.rm = TRUE), 
            n_listings = sum(n_listings, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(-since_year) %>% 
  gt::gt()
